}}\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Rubbadubbers]]'' || {{dts|June 4, 2004}} || {{dts|November 28, 2005}}\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Wow! Wow! Wubbzy!]]''{{refn|group=note|name=credited}} || {{dts|September 1, 2006}} || rowspan=\"2\"| {{dts|September 27, 2009}}<ref name=\"sep2009\"/>{{refn|group=note|name=Nick Jr. channel}}\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Yo Gabba Gabba!]]''{{refn|group=note|name=credited}} || {{dts|August 20, 2007}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2756720/music-on-kids-tv-nick-jr-about-to-get-hip-with-yo-gabba-gabba/|title=Music on Kids TV: Nick Jr about to get hip with Yo Gabba Gabba|first=Drake|last=Lelane|website=MTV News}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Former interstitials===\n{{div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* ''And Then What Happened?'' (2002-2003)\n* ''Art Alive'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''Critter Corner'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''Deja Noggin'' (1999-2002)\n* ''Feetface'' (former mascot; April 1, 2002 \u2013 April 6, 2003)\n* ''Field Trip'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''The Girl With Her Head Coming Off'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Head Buzzers'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Let's Do Math!'' (2005\u20132008)\n* ''Letter and Number Soup'' (1999\u20132002)\n** ''Max and His Alphabet Adventures''\n* ''Little Big Room'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Live@Noggin.com'' (bumpers; 2000\u20132002)\n* ''[[Maggie and the Ferocious Beast]]'' (shorts; 1999\u20132002)\n* ''[[Moose and Zee]]'' (former mascots; April 7, 2003 \u2013 2009)\n* ''Move to the Music'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''My Lucky Family'' (1999-2002)\n* ''Noggin Boogie'' (1999\u20132002)\n** ''Jungle Boogie''\n** ''Nick Jr. Sings''\n* ''Noggin's Choice'' (1999\u20132000)\n* ''Noggin Gold'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Noggin Neighbors'' (2000\u20132002)\n** ''[[Nanalan']]'' (2000\u20132002)\n** ''What's the Buzz with Philomena Fly'' (1999\u20132002)\n** ''Winky Love'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Noggin Presents'' (1999\u20132002; 2007\u20132009)\n** ''Ask Mother Nature'' (1999\u20132002)\n** ''Chickiepoo and Fluff: Barnyard Detectives'' (2007\u20132009)\n** ''[[Peppa Pig]]'' (December 31, 2007 \u2013 2009)\n* ''Nogginoid'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Noggin's Thoughts'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Noggolution'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''[[Oobi (TV series)|Oobi]]'' (shorts and bumpers; 2000\u20132009)\n* ''Out of Your Mind'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Short Films by Short People'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Show and Tell'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''[[Cooking for Kids with Luis]]'' (2005\u20132009)\n* ''Story Time'' (2003\u20132009)\n* ''Think Loudly'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''What's In Heidi's Head?'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''What Sparks You?'' (1999\u20132002)\n* ''Zee's Bookshelf'' (2005\u20132009)\n** ''[[Ebb and Flo]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nickelodeon]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nick Jr.]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nick at Nite]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nicktoons]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by TeenNick]]\n* [[List of films broadcast by Nickelodeon]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nickelodeon}}\n{{Noggin shows}}\n{{programs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noggin}}\n[[Category:Lists of television series by network]]\n", "name_user": "SafariKid2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_programs_broadcast_by_Noggin"}
{"title_page": "Selby Town F.C.", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname  = Selby Town |\n  image     = Selby Town F.C.png|\n  upright   = 0.9|\n  fullname  = Selby Town Football Club |\n  nickname  = The Robins |\n  founded   = 1919 |\n  ground    = Fairfax Plant Hire Stadium<br />[[Selby]], [[North Yorkshire]] |\n  capacity  = 5,000 |\n  chairman  =  Ralph Pearse |\n  manager   =  [[Christian Fox]] |\n  league = {{English football updater|SelbyTow}}\n| season = {{English football updater|SelbyTow2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|SelbyTow3}}|\n  pattern_la1=_redlower|pattern_b1=_whitecollar|pattern_ra1=_redlower|pattern_sh1=_whitebottom|\n  leftarm1=FFFFFF|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FFFFFF|shorts1=FF0000|socks1=FF0000|\n pattern_la2=_black_stripes|pattern_b2=_blackstripes3|pattern_ra2=_black_stripes|\n  leftarm2=EECA38|body2=EECA38|rightarm2=EECA38|shorts2=000000|socks2=000000|\n }}\n'''Selby Town Football Club''' is an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Selby]], North Yorkshire, founded in 1919. They play in the [[Northern Counties East Football League|Northern Counties East League Division One]]. The clubs traditional rivals are [[Goole A.F.C.|Goole]] (with whom they play an annual match, for the right to win the Eric Lawton Cup <ref>{{cite web |title=Match Report: Selby Town 1 GooleAFC 0 |url=http://www.selbytown.co.uk/match-report-selby-town-1-gooleafc-0/ |website=Selby Town Football Club Official Website |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>) and [[Tadcaster Albion F.C.|Tadcaster Albion]].\n\n==History==\nSoon after the club's formation, in 1920 they were entered into the [[Yorkshire Football League]] as a founding member. During the 1930s Selby were one of the most successful clubs in the league, winning it three times before [[World War II]].\n\nAfter the war the club won two more Yorkshire League championships in 1952\u201353 and 1953\u201354 where they also reached the [[FA Cup]] 1st Round. During the 1954\u201355 season, they reached the Second Round of the FA Cup, the furthest in their history; they were knocked out by [[Hastings United F.C.|Hastings United]] 2\u20130.\n\nThe club's record goalscorer is Graham Shepherd who notched up 158 goals between 1963 and 1982. They stayed in the Yorkshire League through its entirety. In 1982 the League became part of the new [[Northern Counties East Football League]] (NCEL), which the Robins were drafted into. Selby became champions of the Northern Counties East League Division One in 1995\u201396 and until 2012 remained in the league they were promoted to; Northern Counties East League Premier Division. However the 2011\u201312 season saw them relegated to the NCEL Division 1<ref name=\"releg2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/relegation-confirmed-for-robins-1-4393881|title=Relegation confirmed for Robins|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505153207/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/relegation-confirmed-for-robins-1-4393881|archivedate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nSelby Town's modern era has seen them reach the 4th round of the [[FA Vase]] in 1995\u201396, the same year they won the NCEL Division One Title under the management of Barry Walker and Tony Carter. In recent seasons the club flourished under the guidance of former Player Bob Lyon, winning the Presidents Cup, Barkston Ash Cup and The Vets over 40s all in 2001.\n\n===2012 relegation===\nThe 2011\u201312 season proved turbulent for Selby Town, with poor results resulting in a series of managerial changes. Leon Sewell was appointed as manager in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/friendly_blow_from_the_seaside_1_3525756|title=Friendly blow from the seaside|date=1 July 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913064548/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/friendly_blow_from_the_seaside_1_3525756|archivedate=13 September 2012}}</ref> He was replaced in September 2011, after only nine games, by Dave Heard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_boss_takes_over_1_3794988|title=New boss takes over|date=23 September 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130421040721/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_boss_takes_over_1_3794988|archivedate=21 April 2013}}</ref> Heard's tenure also proved to be short, with new manager Graham Hodder taking over in January 2012. At this point the club lay in bottom place in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_manager_hopes_to_wake_sleeping_giant_1_4113436|title=New manager hopes to wake sleeping giant|date=6 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120919144323/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_manager_hopes_to_wake_sleeping_giant_1_4113436|archivedate=19 September 2012}}</ref> Outgoing manager Heard claimed that the club was in such financial trouble that it was unable to pay players' travelling expenses<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/players_not_paid_says_outgoing_manager_1_4113400|title=\u2018Players not paid,\u2019 says outgoing manager|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120910173304/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/players_not_paid_says_outgoing_manager_1_4113400|archivedate=10 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 a fourth consecutive 4\u20130 defeat confirmed Selby Town's relegation from the Northern Counties East League Premier Division for the first time since 1996.<ref name=\"releg2012\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\nThe Robins moved from the Bowling Green across town to the current Flaxley Road ground on Richard Street which was purpose built in the early 1950s. \n\nThe club's highest attendance of 7,000 was in 1954 when they played [[Bradford Park Avenue F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] in the [[FA Cup]] 1st Round.\n\nAs a result of a sponsorship deal with the local newspaper, the [[Selby Times]], the Flaxley Road ground was renamed the 'Selby Times Stadium'. In August 2010 a new three season sponsorship deal with Rigid Group (a local packaging manufacturer) led to the stadium being renamed the Rigid Group Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nln24.com/news/story/stadium-deal-for-selby|title=Stadium deal for Selby|publisher=NonLeagueNews|date=5 August 2010|accessdate=14 August 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> From 2012 the stadium is now known as the Fairfax Plant Hire Stadium, FPH being a successful local business which supports the Robins.\n\n==Current staff==\n\nChairman: Ralph Pearse\n\nClub Secretary: Thomas Arkley\n\nMatch Secretary: Mark Aldred\n\nCommercial Manager: Dave Haddock\n\n1st Team Manager : Christian Fox\n\nAssistant Manager: Jonny Bruce \n\nSports Therapist: Zoe Searson & Sarah Holmes\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Division One]]'''\n** Champions: 1995\u201396\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Division Two]] '''\n** Runners-up: 1989\u201390\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League League Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up: 1989\u201390\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Presidents Cup]]'''\n** Winners: 2000\u201301\n* '''[[Yorkshire Football League|Yorkshire League]]'''\n** Champions: 1932\u201333, 1934\u201335, 1935\u201336, 1952\u201353, 1953\u201354\n* '''[[Yorkshire Football League|Yorkshire League]] Cup'''\n** Winners: 1937\u201338, 1953\u201354, 1954\u201355, 1962\u201363\n* '''West Riding Senior Cup'''\n** Winners: 1937\u201338\n* '''West Riding County Cup'''\n** Winners: 1927\u201328, 1948\u201349\n** Runners-up: 2017\u201318\n* '''West Riding Challenge Cup'''\n** Winners: 1934\u201335, 1935\u201336\n* '''Eric Lawton Cup (Formerly known as the Otisdale Cup)'''\n** Winners: 2008-09, 2015-16, 2018-19, 2019-20\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SELBY TOWN RIGID PAPER STADIUM FLAXLEY ROAD STAND AND TERRACE.jpg|Flaxley Road seated stand and covered terrace.\nFIle:Selby town sports centre end terrace.jpg|Sports centre terrace, re-locatable to the new ground.\nFile:Selby town changing rooms with dugouts school pitchside terrace.jpg|Changing rooms with dugouts school pitchside terrace.\nFile:Selby town richard street side with turnstiles clubhouse and bar.jpg|Richard Street side with turnstiles clubhouse and bar.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.selbytown.co.uk Official Website]\n\n{{Northern_Counties_East_Premier}}\n\n{{coord|53|47|05.15|N|1|04|38.20|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Northern Counties East Football League]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Selby]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Yorkshire Football League]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname  = Selby Town |\n  image     = Selby Town F.C.png|\n  upright   = 0.9|\n  fullname  = Selby Town Football Club |\n  nickname  = The Robins |\n  founded   = 1919 |\n  ground    = Fairfax Plant Hire Stadium<br />[[Selby]], [[North Yorkshire]] |\n  capacity  = 5,000 |\n  chairman  =  Ralph Pearse |\n  manager   =  [[Christian Fox]] |\n  league = {{English football updater|SelbyTow}}\n| season = {{English football updater|SelbyTow2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|SelbyTow3}}|\n  pattern_la1=_redlower|pattern_b1=_whitecollar|pattern_ra1=_redlower|pattern_sh1=_whitebottom|\n  leftarm1=FFFFFF|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FFFFFF|shorts1=FF0000|socks1=FF0000|\n pattern_la2=_black_stripes|pattern_b2=_blackstripes3|pattern_ra2=_black_stripes|\n  leftarm2=EECA38|body2=EECA38|rightarm2=EECA38|shorts2=000000|socks2=000000|\n }}\n'''Selby Town Football Club''' is an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Selby]], North Yorkshire, founded in 1919. They play in the [[Northern Counties East Football League|Northern Counties East League Division One]]. The clubs traditional rivals are [[Goole A.F.C.|Goole]] (with whom they play an annual match, for the right to win the Eric Lawton Cup <ref>{{cite web |title=Match Report: Selby Town 1 GooleAFC 0 |url=http://www.selbytown.co.uk/match-report-selby-town-1-gooleafc-0/ |website=Selby Town Football Club Official Website |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>) and [[Tadcaster Albion F.C.|Tadcaster Albion]].\n\n==History==\nSoon after the club's formation, in 1920 they were entered into the [[Yorkshire Football League]] as a founding member. During the 1930s Selby were one of the most successful clubs in the league, winning it three times before [[World War II]].\n\nAfter the war the club won two more Yorkshire League championships in 1952\u201353 and 1953\u201354 where they also reached the [[FA Cup]] 1st Round. During the 1954\u201355 season, they reached the Second Round of the FA Cup, the furthest in their history; they were knocked out by [[Hastings United F.C.|Hastings United]] 2\u20130.\n\nThe club's record goalscorer is Graham Shepherd who notched up 158 goals between 1963 and 1982. They stayed in the Yorkshire League through its entirety. In 1982 the League became part of the new [[Northern Counties East Football League]] (NCEL), which the Robins were drafted into. Selby became champions of the Northern Counties East League Division One in 1995\u201396 and until 2012 remained in the league they were promoted to; Northern Counties East League Premier Division. However the 2011\u201312 season saw them relegated to the NCEL Division 1<ref name=\"releg2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/relegation-confirmed-for-robins-1-4393881|title=Relegation confirmed for Robins|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505153207/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/relegation-confirmed-for-robins-1-4393881|archivedate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nSelby Town's modern era has seen them reach the 4th round of the [[FA Vase]] in 1995\u201396, the same year they won the NCEL Division One Title under the management of Barry Walker and Tony Carter. In recent seasons the club flourished under the guidance of former Player Bob Lyon, winning the Presidents Cup, Barkston Ash Cup and The Vets over 40s all in 2001.\n\n===2012 relegation===\nThe 2011\u201312 season proved turbulent for Selby Town, with poor results resulting in a series of managerial changes. Leon Sewell was appointed as manager in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/friendly_blow_from_the_seaside_1_3525756|title=Friendly blow from the seaside|date=1 July 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913064548/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/friendly_blow_from_the_seaside_1_3525756|archivedate=13 September 2012}}</ref> He was replaced in September 2011, after only nine games, by Dave Heard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_boss_takes_over_1_3794988|title=New boss takes over|date=23 September 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130421040721/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_boss_takes_over_1_3794988|archivedate=21 April 2013}}</ref> Heard's tenure also proved to be short, with new manager Graham Hodder taking over in January 2012. At this point the club lay in bottom place in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_manager_hopes_to_wake_sleeping_giant_1_4113436|title=New manager hopes to wake sleeping giant|date=6 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120919144323/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/new_manager_hopes_to_wake_sleeping_giant_1_4113436|archivedate=19 September 2012}}</ref> Outgoing manager Heard claimed that the club was in such financial trouble that it was unable to pay players' travelling expenses<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/players_not_paid_says_outgoing_manager_1_4113400|title=\u2018Players not paid,\u2019 says outgoing manager|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120910173304/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/sport/football/players_not_paid_says_outgoing_manager_1_4113400|archivedate=10 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 a fourth consecutive 4\u20130 defeat confirmed Selby Town's relegation from the Northern Counties East League Premier Division for the first time since 1996.<ref name=\"releg2012\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\nThe Robins moved from the Bowling Green across town to the current Flaxley Road ground on Richard Street which was purpose built in the early 1950s. \n\nThe club's highest attendance of 7,000 was in 1954 when they played [[Bradford Park Avenue F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] in the [[FA Cup]] 1st Round.\n\nAs a result of a sponsorship deal the Flaxley Road ground was renamed the 'Selby Times Stadium'. In August 2010 a new three season sponsorship deal with Rigid Group (a local packaging manufacturer) led to the stadium being renamed the Rigid Group Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nln24.com/news/story/stadium-deal-for-selby|title=Stadium deal for Selby|publisher=NonLeagueNews|date=5 August 2010|accessdate=14 August 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> From 2012 the stadium is now known as the Fairfax Plant Hire Stadium, FPH being a successful local business which supports the Robins.\n\n==Current staff==\n\nChairman: Ralph Pearse\n\nClub Secretary: Thomas Arkley\n\nMatch Secretary: Mark Aldred\n\nCommercial Manager: Dave Haddock\n\n1st Team Manager : Christian Fox\n\nAssistant Manager: Jonny Bruce \n\nSports Therapist: Zoe Searson & Sarah Holmes\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Division One]]'''\n** Champions: 1995\u201396\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Division Two]] '''\n** Runners-up: 1989\u201390\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League League Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up: 1989\u201390\n* '''[[Northern Counties East Football League Presidents Cup]]'''\n** Winners: 2000\u201301\n* '''[[Yorkshire Football League|Yorkshire League]]'''\n** Champions: 1932\u201333, 1934\u201335, 1935\u201336, 1952\u201353, 1953\u201354\n* '''[[Yorkshire Football League|Yorkshire League]] Cup'''\n** Winners: 1937\u201338, 1953\u201354, 1954\u201355, 1962\u201363\n* '''West Riding Senior Cup'''\n** Winners: 1937\u201338\n* '''West Riding County Cup'''\n** Winners: 1927\u201328, 1948\u201349\n** Runners-up: 2017\u201318\n* '''West Riding Challenge Cup'''\n** Winners: 1934\u201335, 1935\u201336\n* '''Eric Lawton Cup (Formerly known as the Otisdale Cup)'''\n** Winners: 2008-09, 2015-16, 2018-19, 2019-20\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SELBY TOWN RIGID PAPER STADIUM FLAXLEY ROAD STAND AND TERRACE.jpg|Flaxley Road seated stand and covered terrace.\nFIle:Selby town sports centre end terrace.jpg|Sports centre terrace, re-locatable to the new ground.\nFile:Selby town changing rooms with dugouts school pitchside terrace.jpg|Changing rooms with dugouts school pitchside terrace.\nFile:Selby town richard street side with turnstiles clubhouse and bar.jpg|Richard Street side with turnstiles clubhouse and bar.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.selbytown.co.uk Official Website]\n\n{{Northern_Counties_East_Premier}}\n\n{{coord|53|47|05.15|N|1|04|38.20|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Northern Counties East Football League]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Selby]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Yorkshire Football League]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ian3055", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStadium:adding Selby Times link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selby_Town_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Rainbow Bridge (pets)", "text_new": "{{short description|Theme of several works of poetry}}\n{{Other uses|Rainbow bridge (disambiguation){{!}}Rainbow Bridge}}\n[[File:Rainbow-Bridge-heaven.jpg|thumb|300px|The Rainbow Bridge is a meadow where animals wait for their humans to join them, and the bridge that takes them all to Heaven, together.]]\n\nThe ''''' is the theme of several works of poetry written in the 1980s and 1990s that speak of an other-worldly place where [[pet]]s go upon death, eventually to be reunited with their owners. One is a [[prose poetry|prose poem]] whose original creator is uncertain. The other is a six-stanza poem of rhyming pentameter couplets, created by a couple to help ease the pain of friends who lost pets. Each has gained popularity around the world among animal lovers who have [[pet loss|lost a pet]] or wild animals that are cared for. The belief has many antecedents, including similarities to the [[Bifr\u00f6st]] bridge of [[Norse mythology]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/8454288.stm |title=How much can you mourn a pet? |publisher=BBC News |date=13 January 2010 |access-date=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Story ==\n\nThe story tells of a lush green [[meadow]] just \"this side of [[Heaven]]\" (i.e. before one enters into it). Rainbow Bridge is the name of both the meadow and the adjoining pan-prismatic conveyance connecting it to Heaven.\n\nAccording to the story, when a pet dies, it goes to the meadow, restored to perfect health and free of any injuries. The pet runs and plays all day with the others; there is always fresh food and water, and the sun is always shining. However, it is said that while the pet is at peace and happy, they also miss their owner whom they left behind on Earth.\n\nWhen their owner dies, they too arrive at the meadow, and that is when the pet stops playing, turns, sniffs at the air and looks into the distance where they see their beloved owner. Excited, they run as fast as they can, until owner and pet are once more in union. The pet licks its owners in joy while the human looks into the soft eyes of their pet\u2014who might have been absent on Earth, but never absent in their heart. Then side by side, they cross the Rainbow Bridge together into Heaven, never again to be separated.\n\n== Authorship ==\nHaving been circulated widely around the world, the prose poem's original authorship is uncertain. [[About.com]] suggests three presently known contenders to the development of the prose poem:\n\n* Paul C. Dahm, a grief counselor in [[Oregon]], US, said to have written the poem in 1981 and published it in a 1998 book of the same name (1981, {{ISBN|0-9663022-0-6}}).\n* William N. Britton, author of ''Legend of Rainbow Bridge'' (1994, {{ISBN|0-9645018-0-5}})\n* Wallace Sife, head of the Association for Pet Loss and Bereavement, whose poem \"All Pets Go to Heaven\" appears on the association's website as well as in his book ''The Loss of a Pet''\n\nThe genesis of the rhyming poem is  straightforward: spouses Diane and Steve Bodofsky operated a ferret rescue<ref>[http://newrainbowbridge.com The Last Chance Ferret Rescue]</ref> that specialized in gravely ill animals and had many friends whose loss of pets were acutely painful; they wrote the poem for them. But when a local veterinarian asked if they could make it the basis of sympathy cards he might send to his patients, the poem gained popularity. The internet widened the restorative power of the poem internationally.\n\nA ''[[Washington Post]]'' reporter opines that: \"It is, in free verse form, \u201c[[Chicken Soup for the Soul]]\u201d for an exploding [[U.S. Dollars|$]]69 billion pet care industry.<ref name=\"Gardner\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2018/05/01/what-is-the-rainbow-bridge-and-why-do-we-think-dead-pets-cross-it/ |first1=Ann Marie |last1=Gardner |date=May 1, 2018 |title=Animals: What is the rainbow bridge and why do we think dead pets cross it? |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe concept of a paradise where pets wait for their human owners appeared much earlier, in the little-known sequel to ''[[Beautiful Joe]]'', [[Margaret Marshall Saunders]]' book ''Beautiful Joe's Paradise''.  In this green land, the animals do not simply await their owners, but also help each other learn and grow and recover from mistreatment they may have endured in life.  But the animals come to this land, and continue to true heaven, not by a bridge but by balloon.\n\nThe first mention of the \"Rainbow Bridge\" story on the internet is a post on the [[newsgroup]] rec.pets.dogs, dated 7 January 1993, quoting the poem from a 1992 (or earlier) issue of ''Mid-Atlantic Great Dane Rescue League Newsletter'', which in turn is stated to have quoted it from the Akita Rescue Society of America.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rainbow Bridge (Was: Pets passing away. |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.pets.dogs/browse_thread/thread/296f9182afe238a0/368bccee5dd282fd?lnk=st&q=%22cross+the+rainbow+bridge%22&rnum=13&hl=en#368bccee5dd282fd |access-date=9 September 2012}}</ref> Other posts from 1993 suggest it was already well established and being circulated on the Internet at that time, enough for the quotation of even a single line to be expected to be recognized by other newsgroup readers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Breeder \u2013 Lifelong Responsibility |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.pets.dogs/browse_thread/thread/ad01fbda620bb6f4/3b24ad2002e3e12b?lnk=st&q=%22cross+the+rainbow+bridge%22&rnum=6&hl=en#3b24ad2002e3e12b |access-date=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Affectional bond]]\n* [[The Hunt (The Twilight Zone)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Afterlife places]]\n[[Category:Animals in religion]]\n[[Category:Animals and humans]]\n[[Category:Pets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Theme of several works of poetry}}\n{{Other uses|Rainbow bridge (disambiguation){{!}}Rainbow Bridge}}\n[[File:Rainbow-Bridge-heaven.jpg|thumb|300px|The Rainbow Bridge is a meadow where animals wait for their humans to join them, and the bridge that takes them all to Heaven, together.]]\n\nThe '''Rainbow Bridge''' is the theme of several works of poetry written in the 1980s and 1990s that speak of an other-worldly place where [[pet]]s go upon death, eventually to be reunited with their owners. One is a [[prose poetry|prose poem]] whose original creator is uncertain. The other is a six-stanza poem of rhyming pentameter couplets, created by a couple to help ease the pain of friends who lost pets. Each has gained popularity around the world among animal lovers who have [[pet loss|lost a pet]] or wild animals that are cared for. The belief has many antecedents, including similarities to the [[Bifr\u00f6st]] bridge of [[Norse mythology]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/8454288.stm |title=How much can you mourn a pet? |publisher=BBC News |date=13 January 2010 |access-date=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Story ==\n\nThe story tells of a lush green [[meadow]] just \"this side of [[Heaven]]\" (i.e. before one enters into it). Rainbow Bridge is the name of both the meadow and the adjoining pan-prismatic conveyance connecting it to Heaven.\n\nAccording to the story, when a pet dies, it goes to the meadow, restored to perfect health and free of any injuries. The pet runs and plays all day with the others; there is always fresh food and water, and the sun is always shining. However, it is said that while the pet is at peace and happy, they also miss their owner whom they left behind on Earth.\n\nWhen their owner dies, they too arrive at the meadow, and that is when the pet stops playing, turns, sniffs at the air and looks into the distance where they see their beloved owner. Excited, they run as fast as they can, until owner and pet are once more in union. The pet licks its owners in joy while the human looks into the soft eyes of their pet\u2014who might have been absent on Earth, but never absent in their heart. Then side by side, they cross the Rainbow Bridge together into Heaven, never again to be separated.\n\n== Authorship ==\nHaving been circulated widely around the world, the prose poem's original authorship is uncertain. [[About.com]] suggests three presently known contenders to the development of the prose poem:\n\n* Paul C. Dahm, a grief counselor in [[Oregon]], US, said to have written the poem in 1981 and published it in a 1998 book of the same name (1981, {{ISBN|0-9663022-0-6}}).\n* William N. Britton, author of ''Legend of Rainbow Bridge'' (1994, {{ISBN|0-9645018-0-5}})\n* Wallace Sife, head of the Association for Pet Loss and Bereavement, whose poem \"All Pets Go to Heaven\" appears on the association's website as well as in his book ''The Loss of a Pet''\n\nThe genesis of the rhyming poem is  straightforward: spouses Diane and Steve Bodofsky operated a ferret rescue<ref>[http://newrainbowbridge.com The Last Chance Ferret Rescue]</ref> that specialized in gravely ill animals and had many friends whose loss of pets were acutely painful; they wrote the poem for them. But when a local veterinarian asked if they could make it the basis of sympathy cards he might send to his patients, the poem gained popularity. The internet widened the restorative power of the poem internationally.\n\nA ''[[Washington Post]]'' reporter opines that: \"It is, in free verse form, \u201c[[Chicken Soup for the Soul]]\u201d for an exploding [[U.S. Dollars|$]]69 billion pet care industry.<ref name=\"Gardner\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2018/05/01/what-is-the-rainbow-bridge-and-why-do-we-think-dead-pets-cross-it/ |first1=Ann Marie |last1=Gardner |date=May 1, 2018 |title=Animals: What is the rainbow bridge and why do we think dead pets cross it? |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe concept of a paradise where pets wait for their human owners appeared much earlier, in the little-known sequel to ''[[Beautiful Joe]]'', [[Margaret Marshall Saunders]]' book ''Beautiful Joe's Paradise''.  In this green land, the animals do not simply await their owners, but also help each other learn and grow and recover from mistreatment they may have endured in life.  But the animals come to this land, and continue to true heaven, not by a bridge but by balloon.\n\nThe first mention of the \"Rainbow Bridge\" story on the internet is a post on the [[newsgroup]] rec.pets.dogs, dated 7 January 1993, quoting the poem from a 1992 (or earlier) issue of ''Mid-Atlantic Great Dane Rescue League Newsletter'', which in turn is stated to have quoted it from the Akita Rescue Society of America.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rainbow Bridge (Was: Pets passing away. |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.pets.dogs/browse_thread/thread/296f9182afe238a0/368bccee5dd282fd?lnk=st&q=%22cross+the+rainbow+bridge%22&rnum=13&hl=en#368bccee5dd282fd |access-date=9 September 2012}}</ref> Other posts from 1993 suggest it was already well established and being circulated on the Internet at that time, enough for the quotation of even a single line to be expected to be recognized by other newsgroup readers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Breeder \u2013 Lifelong Responsibility |url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.pets.dogs/browse_thread/thread/ad01fbda620bb6f4/3b24ad2002e3e12b?lnk=st&q=%22cross+the+rainbow+bridge%22&rnum=6&hl=en#3b24ad2002e3e12b |access-date=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Affectional bond]]\n* [[The Hunt (The Twilight Zone)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Afterlife places]]\n[[Category:Animals in religion]]\n[[Category:Animals and humans]]\n[[Category:Pets]]\n", "name_user": "160.2.160.24", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainbow_Bridge_(pets)"}
